# Typed errors

Always define named error classes. Never `raise "message"` with a bare string.

Error names should describe what went wrong specifically. Nest them inside
the class that raises them. A name like `BrewInfoError` is good because it
describes the failure (the brew info command failed), not because it
mechanically prefixes the class name.

```ruby
# BAD: bare string
raise "brew info failed"
raise "Could not resolve ref"

# BAD: too generic — what kind of info? whose download?
class InfoError < StandardError; end
class DownloadError < StandardError; end

# GOOD: describes what went wrong
class BrewInfoError < StandardError; end      # brew info command failed
class GitCloneError < StandardError; end      # git clone failed
class GitCheckoutError < StandardError; end   # git checkout failed
class RefResolutionError < StandardError; end # could not resolve a git ref
```

Every typed error must have a corresponding test that asserts the specific class:

```ruby
# In RSpock tests
When "fetching a bad formula"
repository.fetch(bad_id)

Then
raises Dev::Deps::BrewRepository::BrewInfoError
```
